Backend Plan – Users & Accounts
This document outlines my responsibilities (Sierra) for implementing the backend systems related to user accounts, authentication, and user-linked data. I am the backend developer responsible for all functionality in this area, including account creation, login, session handling, and endpoints for schedules and routes.

1. Overview
I am implementing:
The User data model
Sign Up and Login endpoints
Secure password hashing
Authentication and session/token verification
Endpoints for schedule and route data
Validation and access control for all /users/{user_id}/... operations
This backend supports Sam and Kiana on the frontend and integrates with Wilson (schedule) and Quinn (routes).

2. User Model
Each user will be stored with the following fields:
user_id — unique identifier
email — provided during signup
password_hash — securely hashed password
created_at — timestamp
This schema provides a stable foundation for authentication and linking user-specific data.

3. Sign Up Endpoint
Endpoint: POST /api/signup
Input: { email, password }
Process:
Validate email and password
Hash the password
Insert new user into database
Return success or appropriate error (e.g., email already exists)
This endpoint creates a new user and sets up their account in the system.

4. Login Endpoint
Endpoint: POST /api/login
Input: { email, password }
Process:
Look up user by email
Compare provided password with stored password_hash
If valid, generate a session token
If invalid, return an authentication error
The login endpoint allows the user to authenticate and gain access to their personalized data.

5. Sessions & Authentication
Once logged in, the user receives a session token. Authentication responsibilities include:
Verifying the token on each request
Attaching the authenticated user_id to the request
Ensuring only the correct user can modify or view their own data
Rejecting requests without proper authentication
All schedule and route endpoints rely on this.

6. User-Linked Data Endpoints
These endpoints allow storing and retrieving user-specific data. They must always check authentication and ensure that the requesting user is the owner of the resource.

6.1 Schedule Data (Wilson + Backend)
Endpoint: POST /api/users/{user_id}/schedule
Accepts schedule data
Validates that the logged-in user matches the user_id
Stores or updates schedule information
6.2 Route Data (Quinn + Backend)
Endpoint: POST /api/users/{user_id}/routes
Accepts route configuration data
Validates ownership
Stores or updates routes linked to the user

7. Frontend Integration (Sam & Kiana)
The frontend will call all backend endpoints to:
Sign up
Log in
Save schedule
Save routes

My responsibility is to provide:
Clear and consistent JSON responses
Reliable error formats
Predictable authentication behavior
Simple, documented request/response shapes
This ensures smooth integration with the UI.